00:36:51,051 --> 00:36:56,134
Or you can decide, or the publisher can decide for you, we are designing a lifestyle game.

721
00:36:56,855 --> 00:36:59,997
My background is in trading card games and living card games.

722
00:37:00,758 --> 00:37:05,782
So I naturally think in terms of expandability, and most of the games I work on are...

723
00:37:06,622 --> 00:37:11,203
designed to be theoretically infinitely expandable.

724
00:37:12,203 --> 00:37:14,804
So I design usually, the way I do it is design a hook,

725
00:37:16,124 --> 00:37:17,805
a good core game with a really, really,

726
00:37:17,845 --> 00:37:21,566
really solid foundation and theoretically,

727
00:37:22,466 --> 00:37:26,427
theoretically infinite expandable hooks

728
00:37:26,447 --> 00:37:28,447
that I can't necessarily as one designer

729
00:37:28,487 --> 00:37:30,348
that I can't possibly see all ends for.

730
00:37:31,348 --> 00:37:33,688
So that it is not necessarily solvable

731
00:37:35,145 --> 00:37:36,766
If it's not solved by me and my design team,

732
00:37:36,826 --> 00:37:40,048
then it will be not solved in five minutes

733
00:37:40,108 --> 00:37:42,189
by the rest of the internet and the real world.

734
00:37:45,991 --> 00:37:48,132
I think about it, I don't design quite the same way

735
00:37:48,412 --> 00:37:49,753
Eric does, even though he just said it.

736
00:37:50,073 --> 00:37:50,493
No, you don't.

737
00:37:53,155 --> 00:37:54,976
I feel like if you're spending a lot of time

738
00:37:55,016 --> 00:37:56,597
trying to design hooks for expansions

739
00:37:56,657 --> 00:37:58,137
or building your expansions and rolling out

740
00:37:58,157 --> 00:38:00,619
the first six SKUs for this product line,

741
00:38:00,879 --> 00:38:03,400
you're gonna be very disappointed when 99% of the time

742
00:38:03,420 --> 00:38:04,541
that it doesn't come to pass.

743
00:38:05,689 --> 00:38:10,171
I feel like when you design a game, most designers put too much in and have to take it out.

744
00:38:10,211 --> 00:38:15,153
So you probably have a pile of ideas that are already the start of an expansion.

745
00:38:15,673 --> 00:38:19,775
And if not, if it sort of takes off and suddenly the publisher says,

746
00:38:19,815 --> 00:38:22,997
I think we got a hit, we're going back for our third printing and maybe we should do an expansion,

747
00:38:23,337 --> 00:38:26,398
you probably can find some way to get to it pretty quickly.

748
00:38:27,398 --> 00:38:31,120
Some games won't, and some games I've seen that really strained to do it,

749
00:38:31,160 --> 00:38:34,541
where they've had a success and then they expand, and you're like, you didn't need that.

750
00:38:35,267 --> 00:38:37,709
But if there's a faction, there can be more factions.

751
00:38:37,809 --> 00:38:39,410
If there's not a two-player game,

752
00:38:39,430 --> 00:38:40,631
there can be a two-player game.

753
00:38:41,853 --> 00:38:42,653
So it's there.

754
00:38:42,853 --> 00:38:45,055
I don't spend a lot of time planning for them

755
00:38:45,095 --> 00:38:47,898
because you just don't know what's gonna succeed.

756
00:38:47,918 --> 00:38:49,079
I say that and there's season one

757
00:38:49,119 --> 00:38:50,240
on the front of a game that I did.

758
00:38:50,840 --> 00:38:51,021
But.

759
00:38:52,202 --> 00:38:55,545
So Jeff, I mean, you have done the Space Cadets games.

760
00:38:55,885 --> 00:38:57,286
Yes.

761
00:38:57,847 --> 00:38:58,948
Is that what happened?

762
00:38:58,968 --> 00:39:00,549
That you had certain ideas that didn't quite fit

763
00:39:00,589 --> 00:39:02,611
in one of the games so they ended up in another?

764
00:39:03,697 --> 00:39:09,979
Um, no, actually, um, for when we decided to do the expansions for both Space Cadets and Dice Duel,

765
00:39:09,999 --> 00:39:11,780
we really started from scratch.

766
00:39:12,120 --> 00:39:12,441
Okay.

767
00:39:12,461 --> 00:39:15,902
The stuff that wasn't good enough to make the cut the first time just wasn't.

768
00:39:16,689 --> 00:39:17,109
good enough.

769
00:39:17,609 --> 00:39:19,970
We didn't want to try to rehabilitate it and bring it back.

770
00:39:20,030 --> 00:39:22,432
So, yeah, we started from scratch

771
00:39:22,632 --> 00:39:24,413
and designed some new systems and things like that.

772
00:39:24,433 --> 00:39:27,295
The only thing we did say was the name for the expansion

773
00:39:27,355 --> 00:39:28,976
for Space Cadets Dice Duel,

774
00:39:29,316 --> 00:39:31,157
the alternative name was Diefighter.

775
00:39:32,838 --> 00:39:34,279
And I love that name so much,

776
00:39:34,359 --> 00:39:35,479
but the publishers didn't have to do it.

777
00:39:35,519 --> 00:39:36,460
So when we did an expansion,

778
00:39:36,480 --> 00:39:38,161
I said we have to call it Diefighter.

779
00:39:41,323 --> 00:39:42,443
Please don't clap for puns.

780
00:39:45,190 --> 00:39:45,711
A question.

781
00:39:46,912 --> 00:39:47,132
Yes.

782
00:39:47,953 --> 00:39:51,555
Earlier, Aaron Forsythe was asking about the future of potentially disposable games.

783
00:39:52,016 --> 00:39:55,278
You also mentioned Kingdom Death, which is a successful but niche game.

784
00:39:55,799 --> 00:40:00,382
And I'm wondering if you could comment on the potential future of niche games themselves

785
00:40:00,502 --> 00:40:03,245
as an alternative to disposable games.

786
00:40:03,825 --> 00:40:08,289
Games that have very small but rabid audiences, or games that are perhaps so expensive that

787
00:40:08,409 --> 00:40:11,931
people are sort of coerced into playing them, otherwise they didn't justify the purchase.

788
00:40:15,004 --> 00:40:18,245
I like this question because I've never been asked it and don't have an immediate answer

789
00:40:18,425 --> 00:40:22,487
I mean if you talk about niche meaning a very small audience the question I go back to is say like

790
00:40:23,227 --> 00:40:27,729
Well, why did the publisher make it because if the answer is they just wanted it out there and they didn't care about money

791
00:40:27,769 --> 00:40:33,591
Then they're just gonna make the game that they want to play and hopefully there'll be a few hundred people who find it

792
00:40:35,431 --> 00:40:38,776
I used to make a joke about the markability and viability of games and say,

793
00:40:38,796 --> 00:40:42,482
like, don't design a game that takes all day and 17 people to play because it'll never catch on.

794
00:40:42,502 --> 00:40:45,286
And then MegaSiv came out and I was like, oh, or it will.

795
00:40:48,264 --> 00:40:50,464
I don't know, with the growth that we're talking about

796
00:40:50,484 --> 00:40:52,125
and the supply growth and the double digit

797
00:40:52,145 --> 00:40:53,766
year over year growth, there's going to be games

798
00:40:53,806 --> 00:40:55,846
for everyone coming out and it really comes down

799
00:40:55,886 --> 00:40:57,467
to why the publisher wants to do it.

800
00:40:57,507 --> 00:40:59,408
Is it just, is it to get a wide audience?

801
00:40:59,448 --> 00:41:00,788
Is it to get a specific audience?

802
00:41:01,128 --> 00:41:02,609
Is it to take a game that they've played at home

803
00:41:02,669 --> 00:41:04,069
for five years and they really love it

804
00:41:04,089 --> 00:41:05,450
and they just want a few people to play it

805
00:41:05,490 --> 00:41:08,291
so they can sort of pay the bills to go to conventions?

806
00:41:09,791 --> 00:41:11,892
I don't have a clear answer because I think

807
00:41:11,912 --> 00:41:13,753
that there's just so many different reasons

808
00:41:13,773 --> 00:41:16,334
that you would do it, but maybe one of these two people

809
00:41:16,374 --> 00:41:17,594
or three people will have a better one.

810
00:41:18,513 --> 00:41:21,694
Well I mean, I think that, of course there will always be niche games, right?

811
00:41:21,714 --> 00:41:28,556
But it's, as Rob said, whether it's intended to be a niche game is a factor.

812
00:41:29,136 --> 00:41:35,498
And, I mean, board games are physical games, so they're always going to be subject to, in economics, the tyranny of objects.

813
00:41:35,598 --> 00:41:36,318
They're always going to be...

814
00:41:37,470 --> 00:41:42,091
there are going to be hard manufacturing costs and economy of scale,

815
00:41:42,431 --> 00:41:47,273
which you lose once you are printing for a small audience.

816
00:41:48,673 --> 00:41:52,094
The manufacturing is getting cheaper, it's getting more automated,

817
00:41:52,174 --> 00:41:57,495
but the marketplace is also becoming a little bit more and more dominated

818
00:41:57,595 --> 00:42:02,856
by big publishers or conglomerated publishers with more economies of scale.

819
00:42:03,316 --> 00:42:06,517
So as long as there is room in the market for...

820
00:42:07,938 --> 00:42:09,679
less career-oriented or less...

821
00:42:11,401 --> 00:42:11,982
It's starting.

822
00:42:13,443 --> 00:42:13,823
Wow.

823
00:42:14,444 --> 00:42:16,947
I've been doing that in this room all day. I get used to it.

824
00:42:18,508 --> 00:42:19,809
Or publishers that are a little bit less...

825
00:42:21,531 --> 00:42:22,352
profit-motive...

826
00:42:25,735 --> 00:42:27,056
That's really distracting.

827
00:42:27,076 --> 00:42:31,721
It will happen, but...

828
00:42:32,610 --> 00:42:36,652
Again, it depends on... There are a lot of externalities that matter here, right?

829
00:42:36,672 --> 00:42:41,734
A lot of our industry is driven by network externalities.

830
00:42:41,774 --> 00:42:47,516
So gamers meet in game conventions and they meet at game stores, game cafes.

831
00:42:47,856 --> 00:42:54,739
The more they remain viable, the more localized small cottage industries will be able to continue making small games.

832
00:42:55,319 --> 00:42:58,500
But they're going to be subjected to those local economies.

833
00:43:00,019 --> 00:43:01,063
Jeff what do you think? Do you agree?

834
00:43:01,645 --> 00:43:03,050
Yeah, well when I was talking about

835
00:43:04,317 --> 00:43:06,098
where the game industry was at a year ago,

836
00:43:06,158 --> 00:43:07,098
or a year and a half ago,

837
00:43:07,118 --> 00:43:10,279
I said very strongly that it's definitely a push

838
00:43:10,319 --> 00:43:13,779
towards faster, shorter, simpler games.

839
00:43:13,960 --> 00:43:16,020
Love Letter had just come out and was super popular,

840
00:43:16,060 --> 00:43:17,060
and it just seemed like nobody,

841
00:43:17,520 --> 00:43:18,361
before it was like, you know,

842
00:43:18,741 --> 00:43:19,961
when I was growing up, people used to play

843
00:43:20,001 --> 00:43:20,961
three, four hour games,

844
00:43:21,461 --> 00:43:23,202
and then it was like two hour games was normal,

845
00:43:23,482 --> 00:43:25,262
90 minutes, and now it's like if it's over 60 minutes,

846
00:43:25,882 --> 00:43:26,863
nobody wants to look at it.

847
00:43:26,903 --> 00:43:28,543
But at the same time, like you said,

848
00:43:28,563 --> 00:43:29,363
you've got those,

849
00:43:29,383 --> 00:43:31,204
it seems like there's a little pushback now,

850
00:43:31,244 --> 00:43:32,564
and you've got these big,

851
00:43:33,204 --> 00:43:37,507
heavy games that are coming out that are finding a market and are in there.

852
00:43:37,607 --> 00:43:43,930
So I'm interested to see kind of if it's just, you know, going to be pulling on both ends or where that's going to end up.

853
00:43:45,351 --> 00:43:48,433
But I would love to see, I mean, I think in some sense that

854
00:43:49,333 --> 00:43:52,775
because of the physicality of board games that there's opportunities that are missed.

855
00:43:52,916 --> 00:43:58,599
I, you know, I would love to be able to do a series of really quick one-off type designs to explore

856
00:43:59,379 --> 00:44:00,481
different issues and things like that,

857
00:44:00,501 --> 00:44:03,084
which I think the video game world does fantastically

858
00:44:04,085 --> 00:44:07,930
to have more like art projects in a way than games.

859
00:44:08,450 --> 00:44:10,312
I'd love to be able to do a quick game about

860
00:44:10,933 --> 00:44:13,676
being a refugee and experiencing life as a refugee

861
00:44:13,716 --> 00:44:15,418
and the choices that you make and things like that.

