00:46:33,672 --> 00:46:35,293
Absolutely. Well, I mean, to speak to number one,

910
00:46:36,273 --> 00:46:37,934
fuck them. Follow your passion.

911
00:46:38,034 --> 00:46:38,194
Wow.

912
00:46:45,806 --> 00:46:52,048
Number two, yeah, number two, we've talked about this a lot, actually.

913
00:46:53,509 --> 00:46:55,650
Do you want to tell my insane story?

914
00:46:56,750 --> 00:47:01,512
You have so many, I actually don't know which one you mean.

915
00:47:01,632 --> 00:47:03,593
The throwing away of every...

916
00:47:04,413 --> 00:47:06,194
Oh, yeah, you did do that, didn't you?

917
00:47:08,277 --> 00:47:13,846
Eric like last year was putting up on Twitter that he had thrown away all of his prototypes like physically digitally gone

918
00:47:14,306 --> 00:47:18,352
Not set him aside, and I was like he must be speaking metaphorically

919
00:47:18,493 --> 00:47:24,261
And then we were working on a project and we took a Christmas break and we came back and we had spent

920
00:47:25,197 --> 00:47:29,300
Eight months on it, and hours and hours of meetings, and I had flown to Toronto, we had played it,

921
00:47:29,840 --> 00:47:31,701
and I was like, I'm not feeling it.

922
00:47:32,202 --> 00:47:36,164
He's like, me neither, and he was just done, and we threw it away,

923
00:47:37,005 --> 00:47:40,367
and started on something new, and it was actually one of the best decisions we ever made,

924
00:47:40,427 --> 00:47:43,710
because we would have labored and labored to have a game that was like a B-minus,

925
00:47:44,750 --> 00:47:48,733
and we just both could see it. I'm not sure that I would have had the bravery to like...

926
00:47:49,816 --> 00:47:53,097
throw it away quite like that, or literally throw things away like you do.

